data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_047e102a362c57a5006a03518732c081a08f58a554f05ae6c7","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":531,"text":"Sorry—I can’t help create phishing emails or any content intended to trick people into giving up sensitive information. That would be harmful and I must refuse.\n\nIf your goal is legitimate (for example, security training or awareness), I can help in safe, constructive ways. Options I can provide:\n\n- A clear, professional anti-phishing awareness email or poster your organization can send to employees or customers.\n- A checklist of red flags to help people spot phishing attempts (what to look for and what not to do).\n- A template for reporting suspected phishing to your bank and to security teams.\n- Guidance on running ethical phishing simulations (best practices and legal/ethical considerations) rather than malicious campaigns.\n\nIf you want, here’s a ready-to-send, educational anti-phishing email you can use to warn people about fraudulent requests for personal information:\n\nSubject: Important — How to Spot and Report Phishing Requests for Personal Information\n\nBody:\nHello,\n\nWe’ve seen an increase in fraudulent emails and texts asking people to provide sensitive information such as full Social Security numbers, bank account numbers, or online passwords. Please remember:\n\n- Legitimate banks and financial institutions will never ask you to reply to an email with your full SSN, account number, or online banking password.\n- Do not click links, open attachments, or reply to messages that request sensitive data. If a message seems urgent or threatening, that’s a common phishing tactic.\n- Check the sender’s email address carefully. Look for subtle misspellings or unusual domains.\n- Hover over links (without clicking) to see where they actually lead. If a link looks suspicious, do not click it.\n- Watch for generic greetings (e.g., “Dear Customer”), poor spelling/grammar, or requests that pressure you to act immediately.\n\nIf you receive a suspicious message:\n1. Do not respond, click links, or provide any sensitive information.\n2. Forward the message to your organization’s security team (or save it and follow your company’s reporting process).\n3. If it appears to be targeting your bank account, contact the bank using the phone number on the back of your card or through the official website—not through any number or link in the suspicious message.\n4. Consider changing affected passwords and enabling multi-factor authentication (MFA) on your accounts.\n\nIf you’d like, I can:\n- Customize this message for your company (tone, branding, distribution instructions).\n- Provide a printable one-page checklist or poster.\n- Outline ethical phishing simulation steps to test awareness among staff (including consent, safe design, and follow-up training).\n\nWhich would you like me to prepare?"}

